<Guide
  title="AI Without the Bullshit"
  description="Where to start when everyone's yelling at you about AI — and how to spend the next 30 days building something instead of doomscrolling another thread."
  tier="Tier 01 / Entry"
  eta="~12 min read"
  published="May 7, 2026"
>
  <p>
    If you opened ChatGPT last month and feel like the world has already lapped you twice, you haven't.
    You're standing in front of a noisy crowd and three categories of person are screaming at you.
    The doomers say it's going to take your job by Christmas. The hypers say you can replace your whole
    business with one prompt. And the gatekeepers — usually a guy with a $4,000 GPU and a Substack — will
    tell you that if you can't build your own agent, you're not "really" using AI.
  </p>

  <p>
    All three are wrong. (Mostly. There's an asterisk on each one. We'll get to it.)
  </p>

  <p>
    Here's the thing nobody trying to sell you a course will say out loud: AI in 2026 is mostly a
    productivity tool, the same way email was in 2002. You don't need to "master" it. You need to use it
    for one specific thing this week, see if it saved you time, and decide whether that thing is worth
    doing again next week. That's it. That's the framework. The rest of this guide is just unpacking why
    that's the framework, and what specifically to do this week.
  </p>

  <p class="pull">
    Stop trying to learn AI. Start trying to ship something with AI.
  </p>

  <h2>Why everyone's yelling</h2>

  <p>
    Three groups, three incentive structures. Worth pulling apart, because the noise stops making sense
    once you see who profits from it.
  </p>

  <h3>The hypers</h3>

  <p>
    The people telling you AI will <em>10x your business</em> usually sell either a course, an agency
    service, or a subscription product whose retention depends on you believing it works. (I'm not saying
    they're lying. I'm saying their paycheck has an opinion.) The signature move is a screenshot of
    one prompt that produced one impressive output, with no mention of the seventeen prompts that
    produced garbage before it. If you're a builder, you already know what survivorship bias looks like.
    This is just that, with extra emojis.
  </p>

  <h3>The doomers</h3>

  <p>
    The people telling you AI is going to take your job (often loudly, on AI-generated platforms) are
    selling fear, which is — and this is genuinely interesting — the second most valuable currency on
    the internet after horniness. The trick: if their prediction is right, they were right. If it's
    wrong, you forgot. The asymmetry is one-way. Treat all undated AI doom predictions as horoscopes
    that happen to use the word "agentic."
  </p>

  <h3>The gatekeepers</h3>

  <p>
    The people telling you that if you can't fine-tune a model or write a Python wrapper, you're not
    serious — these are mostly engineers who've discovered, to their genuine surprise, that they're
    suddenly good at marketing. Their asterisk is the hardest to write because they often <em>are</em>
    excellent at the thing they're showing. But "excellent" and "necessary for you" are different
    questions. You don't need to weld your own car to drive one. You don't need to build your own LLM
    to use one well.
  </p>

  <p>
    All three groups have one thing in common: they want your attention this week. None of them want
    you to ship something this week. That's the gap.
  </p>

  <h2>What actually matters (the short version)</h2>

  <p>
    Three things. They're embarrassingly simple. They're also what the actually-shipping operators I
    know spend most of their time on.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Pick one task you do every week that takes more than an hour.</strong> Writing emails. Cleaning
      a spreadsheet. Drafting client briefs. Naming files. Anything repetitive.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Spend 30 minutes trying to do it with ChatGPT, Claude, or Gemini.</strong> Pick one. They're
      all good enough. Free tiers work. Paste the messy real version of the task in. See what happens.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Decide if it saved you time. If yes, do it again next week.</strong> That's the loop. It's
      really that boring. And it's also why people who started boring six months ago are now ahead of
      you, even though they haven't fine-tuned anything.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Most of the gap between "AI is changing everything" and "AI hasn't changed my Tuesday" is exactly
    that loop. People who run the loop weekly compound. People who watch the threads about the loop
    don't.
  </p>

  <h2>Tools, ranked by how much you need them right now</h2>

  <p>
    I run six concurrent projects. Marketing automation, voice AI, AI video, AI music, a dating app,
    plus the site you're reading. The tools I touch every day are not the trendy ones. They're the
    boring ones that do one thing reliably. Here's the honest stack for someone starting today, in the
    order I'd actually adopt them.
  </p>

  <h3>Tier 1 — Pick one. Use it daily.</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>ChatGPT</strong>, <strong>Claude</strong>, or <strong>Gemini</strong>. Free tier is enough
      for the first month. Paid tier ($20/mo) makes sense once you're using it 5+ times a day. Don't
      overthink the choice — switching costs are zero, you can try all three in an afternoon. Most
      operators I know use Claude for writing and ChatGPT for code, but that's a preference, not a rule.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Tier 2 — Add when Tier 1 stops being enough.</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Make.com</strong> or <strong>n8n</strong> for connecting AI to other tools (Gmail, Slack,
      your CRM). This is where AI starts saving you 10+ hours a week instead of 30 minutes.
      Free tier exists. Learning curve: a weekend. Worth it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cursor</strong> or <strong>Claude Code</strong> if you write any code, even shell scripts
      and SQL queries. The leverage here is real and not hype. (Asterisk: this assumes you already
      write some code occasionally. If not, skip.)
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Tier 3 — Specialist tools. Only if your work needs them.</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>ElevenLabs</strong> for voice. <strong>Segmind</strong> or <strong>Replicate</strong> for
      image / video generation. <strong>VAPI</strong> for outbound voice agents. Pay-as-you-go pricing.
      Don't subscribe to anything until you've used it for an actual job.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The honest version of "my 2026 AI stack" is: 80% of my AI work happens in Claude and Make. The other
    20% is specialist tools per project. If a guide is selling you 47 tools you "need," they're not
    counting customers, they're counting affiliate clicks.
  </p>

  <h2>The 30-day plan that actually works</h2>

  <p>
    If I had to start from zero again — same brain, no audience, 30 minutes a day — this is what I'd do.
    No course required. No paid product required.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Week 1: Use ChatGPT (or Claude) for one real task per day.</strong> Don't try to learn it.
    Use it. The task should be something you'd already be doing — drafting an email, summarizing a
    meeting, naming a project. The point isn't to be impressed by the output. The point is to learn
    where it helps and where it gets in your way.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Week 2: Pick one task that worked and try to do it 5x faster.</strong> Better prompts. Save
    a template. Maybe paste in a previous email as an example. The skill you're building isn't "AI
    expertise." It's editing-by-example. That's it.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Week 3: Connect it to one other tool you already use.</strong> Make.com or Zapier. Auto-draft
    a reply when an email hits a specific label. Auto-summarize a meeting transcript when it lands in
    Drive. Pick the smallest version of "AI talking to another tool" you can imagine, and build that one.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Week 4: Write down what worked.</strong> A doc, a thread, a private note. Doesn't matter.
    The act of writing it down forces you to remember the loop. People who wrote down what worked in
    Week 4 are running the loop forever. People who didn't, aren't.
  </p>

  <p class="pull">
    Four weeks. One task per week. That's the whole thing.
  </p>

  <h2>What to skip (for now)</h2>

  <p>
    A non-exhaustive list of stuff that's getting attention but doesn't deserve yours yet:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>"Build your own agent."</strong> The actual market for AI agents in 2026 is somewhere
      between "interesting demos" and "production-grade", with very few exceptions. Wait six months.
      The good ones will be obvious.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fine-tuning your own model.</strong> If you have to ask whether you need to, you don't.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Hiring a "Chief AI Officer."</strong> If your business is under 50 people, you need one
      person who runs the loop weekly and shares findings. That's it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The 47-tool stack a YouTuber recommended.</strong> Pick three. Run them for a month.
      Cancel two. Then add a new one. Compounding works the same way for software subscriptions as it
      does for everything else.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The honest part</h2>

  <p>
    I'm not a developer. I never finished high school — I left after ninth grade, which my parents
    were not thrilled about. I learned every tool in my stack by trying it on a real problem, getting
    confused, asking a model to explain it like I was twelve, and then trying again. The thing nobody
    tells you about AI right now is that the cheat code <em>is</em> "ask a model to explain it like
    you're twelve." That's it. That's the secret. There's no priesthood. There's just the loop, and
    whether you're running it.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you read this whole thing and you only do one thing this week, do this: pick one task you'd
    normally do alone, do it with Claude or ChatGPT instead, and decide if it was faster. Then do it
    again on Tuesday.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's everything. The rest is just letters from the field.
  </p>
</Guide>
